# Simple Python Projects

Welcome to the "Simple Python Projects" repository! This repository contains a collection of Python projects designed to help you learn and practice Python programming in a fun and interactive way. Whether you're a beginner or an experienced developer, these projects offer a variety of challenges and opportunities to improve your Python skills.

## Projects Included

1. **Tic-Tac-Toe Game:** Play the classic Tic-Tac-Toe game against a computer opponent. This project demonstrates basic game logic, user input handling, and simple AI.

2. **Minesweeper Game:** Test your deduction skills with this classic Minesweeper game. Uncover hidden mines and clear the board safely. This project focuses on grid-based game mechanics and algorithms.

3. **Sudoku Solver:** Solve Sudoku puzzles with ease using this Sudoku solver. You can also input your Sudoku puzzles for the solver to complete. This project covers algorithmic problem-solving and recursive functions.

## Getting Started

To get started with any of these projects, navigate to the respective project folder and follow the instructions provided in the project's README.

## Prerequisites

All you need to run these projects is a Python interpreter installed on your computer. Python is a versatile and beginner-friendly programming language. If you don't have Python installed, you can download it from the [official Python website](https://www.python.org/downloads/).

## How to Contribute

We welcome contributions from the community to make these projects even better! If you have an idea for a new project, want to improve existing code, or spot a bug, please feel free to open an issue or submit a pull request.

1. Fork the repository.
2. Clone your forked repository: `git clone https://github.com/your-username/Simple-Python-Projects.git`
3. Create a new branch for your changes: `git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name`
4. Make your changes and commit them: `git commit -m "Add your message here"`
5. Push your changes to your forked repository: `git push origin feature/your-feature-name`
6. Open a pull request to the main repository.

